Using Data Science to Analyze Temperature Change Across the Globe

Wenjie Wei

Introduction¶

Since the start of the Industrial Revolution in 1760, hummanity has enjoyed unprecented levels of productivity and efficiency. While the rise of large-scale industry has its benefits, many have also recognized its devastating side effects. Chief among them is global warming, which is the phenomenon of increasing average temperatures of the Earth's atmosphere. Many researchers have concluded that global warming is disastrous to the Earth's ecosystem and will eventually cause irreversible damage to the planet. Even though this climate crisis is global, its impact may not be equally severe in different parts of the world. As such, understanding the effects of global warming in different regions of the globe is important to better prepare for and prevent environmental disasters in those areas.

The purpose of this tutorial, then, is to examine the changes in temperature over time based on location through data science. By the end, I hope to provide insights into the Data Science Pipeline, demonstrate that our planet is indeed becoming warmer, and create models to predict future temperature changes based on location.

Data Collection¶

The first part of the data lifecycle is collecting data and obtaining a useful dataset. Sometimes the data is already collected and can be used as is. Other times, you may need to collect data from websites via scraping , which is process of extracting information from a website. The dataset I am using comes from kaggle.com and is hosted on GitHub to make them publicly accessible. Important technologies used: pandas.

Data Management¶

After we have the dataset, we want to make sure that the data is useful for analysis. In this second part of the data lifecycle, we clean and organinze our data. Note that datasets are very diverse and this process can vary significantly depending on your raw data. The processes below are only representative of how this particular dataset needs to be modified to fit our purposes. You can learn more about data management here. Important technologies used: NumPy.

First we want to determine if there are missing values in the dataset.

There are also other ways to deal with missing data, which you can find here.

In [6]:
import numpy as np

# Convert our date values into datetime objects
df["dt"] = pd.to_datetime(df.dt)
# Change the column names to more understandable ones
df.rename(columns={"dt":"Date"}, inplace=True)

# Convert Latitude and Longitude column into floats
# Note that West(W) and South(S) indicate negative values
df["Latitude"] = np.where(df["Latitude"].str.find("S") != -1, "-" + df["Latitude"], df["Latitude"])
df["Longitude"] = np.where(df["Longitude"].str.find("W") != -1, "-" + df["Longitude"], df["Longitude"])

# We extract only the numerical part and convert it o float
df["Latitude"] = df["Latitude"].str.extract('(-?\d+.\d+)', expand=False)
df["Latitude"] = df["Latitude"].astype(float)
df["Longitude"] = df["Longitude"].str.extract('(-?\d+.\d+)', expand=False)
df["Longitude"] = df["Longitude"].astype(float)

# Also want to add an Year and Month column for processing purposes
df["Year"] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df["Date"]).year
df["Month"] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df["Date"]).month

# Set the date as index
df = df.set_index("Date")

df.head()

Here, I renamed the "dt" column to "Date" in order to more appropriately describe the column and provide greater clarity. Furthermore, we previously learned that the date column was seen as an object/string. As such, I converted the type of values in the date column into datetime objects and set them as the index of our data frame. This will help us later in visualizing the data since it makes the index more time aware. I converted latitude and longitude values into floats, which will allow us to visualize these data points on a map. I also extracted the year and month of the date so that they can easily be used individually later on. This all serves to make life easier for the subsequent phases of the Data Science Pipeline.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In this phase, our goal is to use visualization, summary statistics, and modeling to explore and discover various aspects our data. Exploratory data analysis is the last step before hypothesis testing and serves to inform what approaches we should take. This process varies greatly depending on your data and the emphasis is on the spirit of exploration. You can learn more about exploratory data analysis techniques here. Important technologies used: seaborn, matplotlib, folium.

We first take a look at our data statistics to help determine our next steps.

temp1["Change"] = 0

# Calculate change in temperature for each city
for i, row in temp.iterrows():
    if i % 2 == 0:
        previous = temp.iloc[i]["AverageTemperature"]
    else:
        temp1.at[int(i/2),"Change"] = temp.iloc[i]["AverageTemperature"] - previous

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning Predictions¶

During hypothesis testing, we test the assumuptions we've made based on the exploratory data analysis. To test the likelihood that a hypothesis is true, we establish the mutually exclusive null and alternative hypotheses. The null hypothesis represents no change whereas the alternative hypothesis represents change. We compute the probability that a null hypothesis is true based on a p-Value. Learn more about the details here. In this section, we will also use various machine learning algorithms to predict future temperature changes in various countries. Important technologies used: statsmodels , sklearn.

We first want to determine if there is indeed an upwards trend in global temperatures. From what we saw in the previous phase, let the null hypothesis be that there is no relationship between year and average temperature. We fit a linear regression model to determine the p-Value.

In [22]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Fit a linear model with AverageTemperature as the response and Year as the predictor
lm = sm.OLS.from_formula("AverageTemperature ~ Year", df)
result = lm.fit()
result.summary()

We see that the p-Value (P>|t|) for Year is 0. This indicates that the likelyhood that the Year coefficient is measured by chance is 0%. In other words, there is a 0% chance that the Year variable has no affect on AverageTemperature, our dependent variable. As such, we can reject the null hypothesis. Moreover, we see by the coef value that global temperatures have been increasing by 0.0102 celsius every year since 1900. This suggests that since then, Earth's average land temperature has increased about 1.2444 celsius. Learn more about interpreting linear regression summaries here.

During the exploratory data analysis phase, we also saw that there is a dependence between AverageTemperature and Country. This means that each country has unique effects on AverageTemperature over time. As such, including an interaction term for Country and Year in the regression model will likely improve its accuracy. This time, we will use tools found in sklearn to create a predictive model of the data. The model, then, will help us predict future temperature changes based on country. Note that there are many more machine learning algorithms than just regression. You can find some of them, including linear regression, here.

In [23]:
# Obtain independent varibles by themselves
x = df.drop(["AverageTemperature"], axis=1)

# Obtain dependent varible by itself
y = df["AverageTemperature"]

# Handle categorical independent variables
countries = pd.get_dummies(x, drop_first=True)
# Drop the extra columns
x = x.drop(["Country"], axis=1)
x = x.drop(["Year"], axis=1)
# Reattach the new variables
x = pd.concat([x,countries], axis=1)

# Split data into training and testing sets
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.20, random_state = 4)

# Get the regression object and use it to fit the training data
LR = LinearRegression()
LR.fit(x_train,y_train)

# Feed the model the test data and retreive its outputs
y_prediction =  LR.predict(x_test)
R2 = r2_score(y_test,y_prediction)
print("R-squared: " + str(R2) )

R-squared: 0.9959873887639692

To train our linear regression model, we used 80% of our data. To test it, we used the remaining 20%. A seed number (random_state) is also included so that these results are reproducible. You can learn more about splitting datasets here. The R-squared value ranges from 0 to 1 and in essence represents how well the regression model fits the data. The closer to 1, the better the model is fitted. Based on its R-squared score of 0.9959827307464498, our model is extremely well fitted to the data.

However, because our model uses multiple independent variables, we also need to look at its adjusted R-squared value. You can learn more about the differences between the two here.

In [24]:
# Calculate adjusted R2 based on its formula
# Sample size
n = .8 * 5586
# Number of independent variables
p = 2
AR2 = 1-(1-R2)*(n-1)/(n-p)
print("Adjusted R-squared: " + str(AR2))

Adjusted R-squared: 0.9959864904449856

We see that the adjusted R-squared value is still very high, which confirms the efficacy of our model. As such, we have obtained a model that can be used to predict future temperature changes based on location.

Let's see a summary of our model to gain more insight.

Insights¶

During this phase of the Data Science pipeline, we want to communicate what we have learned throughtout the analysis.

The overall temperature of the Earth has been steadily increasing since the Industrial Revolution. Since 1900, average global temperatures have already risen by about 1.24 celsius. By the models we produced, we can expect to experience another overall temperature increase of 1.02 celsius in the next 100 years. This change in climate has the effect of disrupting ecosystems and bring about widespread extreme weather. Thus, it is in the best interest of all people and institutions to respond before irreversible damage is dealt.

Based on what we have observed while analyzing the relationships between location and temperature change over time, we also learned that while most countries are experiencing an increase in temperatures, some are experiencing greater increases than others. Our analysis has shown that this is likely not because of location but some other factors that make certain countries more susceptible to global warming. As such, we can use the models we produced through machine learning to determine which countries are more at risk and help inform local measures to combat climate change.

For further research, I suggest including socio-economic data for each country so that we might be able to better understand why countries experience differing levels of temperature change. Moreover, we can include statistics about the health of ecosystems over time in order to understand the impact that global warming has on Earth systems.
